
class Solution {
    public class Info implements Comparable<Info> {
        int val;
        int row;
        int col;

        public Info(int val, int row, int col) {
            this.val = val;
            this.row = row;
            this.col = col;
        }

        @Override
        public int compareTo(Info other) {
            if (this.col != other.col) {
                return Integer.compare(this.col, other.col); 
            }
            if (this.row != other.row) {
                return Integer.compare(this.row, other.row); 
            }
            if(this.val != other.val){
                return Integer.compare(this.val, other.val); 
            }
            return 0;
        }
    }


    public List<List<Integer>> verticalTraversal(TreeNode root) {
        if (root == null) {
            return new ArrayList<>();
        }


        List<List<Integer>> arr = new ArrayList<>();
        List<Info> list = new ArrayList<>();

        information(root, list, 0, 0);

        Collections.sort(list);

        List<Integer> result = new ArrayList<>();

        Info l = list.get(0);
        int col = l.col;

        for(int i = 0; i < list.size(); i++){
            Info j = list.get(i);

            if(col == j.col){
                result.add(j.val);
            }
            else{
                arr.add(new ArrayList<>(result));
                result = new ArrayList<>();
                result.add(j.val);
                col = j.col;
            }
        }

        arr.add(new ArrayList<>(result));
        return arr;
    }

    public void information(TreeNode root,  List<Info> list, int row, int col){
        if(root == null){
            return;
        }
        list.add(new Info(root.val, row, col));
        information(root.left, list, row+1, col-1);
        information(root.right, list, row+1, col+1);
        return;
    }
}


Problem Description

You are given three strings:

s1
s2
s3

Your task is to determine whether s3 is formed by interleaving the characters of s1 and s2.

An interleaving means:

All characters of s1 and s2 are used exactly once.
The relative order of characters in s1 remains the same.
The relative order of characters in s2 remains the same.
Characters from s1 and s2 can be mixed together.

Return:

true if s3 is an interleaving of s1 and s2.
false otherwise.
Example 1
Input
s1 = "aabcc"
s2 = "dbbca"
s3 = "aadbbcbcac"
Output
true
Explanation

s3 is created by mixing characters from s1 and s2 while keeping the order of characters in each string.

One possible interleaving is:

s1 : a a b c c
      | |   | |
s2 :   d b b c a
        | | | |
-----------------
s3 : a a d b b c b c a c

The order of characters in both s1 and s2 is preserved.

Example 2
Input
s1 = "aabcc"
s2 = "dbbca"
s3 = "aadbbbaccc"
Output
false
Explanation

It is impossible to form s3 while maintaining the order of characters in both s1 and s2.

Example 3
Input
s1 = ""
s2 = ""
s3 = ""
Output
true
Explanation

All strings are empty, so s3 is a valid interleaving.

Constraints
0 <= s1.length, s2.length <= 100
0 <= s3.length <= 200
s1, s2, and s3 consist of lowercase English letters.
Approach
First, check if the length of s1 + s2 equals the length of s3.
Starting from the first character of s3, try to match it with the current character of either s1 or s2.
If it matches s1, move to the next character in s1.
If it matches s2, move to the next character in s2.
Continue until all characters of s3 are processed.
Since there can be multiple valid choices, use Dynamic Programming (DP) or Recursion + Memoization to avoid repeated calculations.
Time Complexity
O(m × n)

where:

m = s1.length()
n = s2.length()
Space Complexity
O(m × n)
